com.javax0.jdsl

Class GrammarDefinition

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.javax0.jdsl.GrammarDefinition
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Analyzer

    public abstract class GrammarDefinition
extends Object
implements Analyzer
    This class is a singleton to ease the build of grammar. To use it you can import the field is statically and then use the utility functions. 
     import static com.javax0.jdsl.Grammar.is;
 ListExecutor ifExecutor = new IfExecutor();
 PassThroughAnalyzer command = definedLater();
 Analyzer ifCommand = list(ifExecutor
                ,kw("if","("),expression,kw(")"),command
                ,is.optional(is.list(kw("else"),command,kw("endif"))));
 command.define( or(ifCommand,whileCommand,letCommand,printCommand) );
 Analyzer programAnalyzer = is.many(command);

      • kw

        public final Analyzer kw(String... keywords)
        Create a TerminalSymbolAnalyzer if there is only one argument or a NoExecutorListAnalyzer containing the TerminalSymbolAnalyzers created for the arguments.

        Note that using 

         list(kw("A"), kw("B"))
        is equivalent to 
         list(kw("A", "B"))
        when calling list(Analyzer...) or #list(ListExecutor, Analyzer...) because the NoExecutorListAnalyzers get flattened into the list.

        Note that you can not use or(kw("A","B")) instead of or(kw("A"),kw("B")). Alternative analyzer does NOT flatten keyword lists.

        Note that this version of themethod creates TerminalSymbolAnalyzer that compares the keywords case sensitive. If you want case insensitive keywords, then use

      • later

        public final PassThroughAnalyzer later(String name)
        Returns a new PassThroughAnalyzer analyzer. This way a grammar element can be defined later than it is used. This is needed when there is some recursive (circular) definition in the grammar. (And usually there is.)

        The parameter name is only used in the debug logs when the grammar is debugged.

      • later

        public final PassThroughAnalyzer later()

      • list

        public final Analyzer list(Factory<ListExecutor> listExecutorFactory,
            Analyzer... analyzers)
        Create a ListAnalyzer that uses the executor listExecutor and contains the analyzers in a list.

        If the analyzers contain NoExecutorListAnalyzer instances then these are replaced by the elements of their lists. The flattening is done recursively so long as long there are NoExecutorListAnalyzer in any of the lists. This means that the method kw(String...) can be used with many arguments and when used in the argument list of a #list(ListExecutor, Analyzer...) then they will have the same effect as if the strings were used individually to define terminal symbols.

      • list

        public final Analyzer list(Analyzer... analyzers)
        Same as #list(ListExecutor, Analyzer...) except it does not use an external executor, but rather creates a new SimpleListExecutor . This is quite handy in many cases when the underlying elements in the list should simply be executed one after the other, or when there is nothing to execute in a list.

      • or

        public final Analyzer or(Analyzer... analyzers)
        Creates an AlternativesAnalyzer with the arguments as alternatives.

      • optional

        public final Analyzer optional(Factory<ListExecutor> listExecutorFactory,
                Analyzer analyzer)
        Creates a SequenceAnalyzer with zero min value and one max value. This means that the underlying analyzer need not be matched, or may be matched once.

      • many

        public final Analyzer many(Factory<ListExecutor> listExecutorFactory,
            Analyzer analyzer,
            int min,
            int max)
        Creates a sequence analyzer that uses the analyzer to at least min and at most max times. Each time the analyzer is successful it creates a new ListExecutor using the listExecutorFactory.

      • many

        public final Analyzer many(Analyzer analyzer,
            int min,
            int max)
        Same as many(Factory, Analyzer, int, int) but it does not accept any factory. Instead it uses a SimpleListExecutorFactory.

      • manyOptional

        public final Analyzer manyOptional(Factory<ListExecutor> listExecutorFactory,
                    Analyzer analyzer)
        Creates a sequence analyzer that analyzes zero or more times. On the argument see many(Factory, Analyzer, int, int) with min and max set to zero, and infinite.

      • manyOptional

        public final Analyzer manyOptional(Analyzer analyzer)
        Same as manyOptional(Factory, Analyzer) but it does not accept any factory. Instead it uses a SimpleListExecutorFactory.

      • many

        public final Analyzer many(Factory<ListExecutor> listExecutorFactory,
            Analyzer analyzer)
        Same as manyOptional(Factory, Analyzer) but the min value is one instead of zero. This means that the structure to be analyzed by the analyzer has to be present at least once.

      • many

        public final Analyzer many(Analyzer analyzer)
        Same as many(Factory, Analyzer) but uses the SimpleListExecutorFactory.
